23"}
{"id":"1909.03604","submitter":"Denali Molitor","authors":"Robert Gower, Denali Molitor, Jacob Moorman, Deanna Needell","title":"Adaptive Sketch-and-Project Methods for Solving Linear Systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present new adaptive sampling rules for the sketch-and-project method for\nsolving linear systems. To deduce our new sampling rules, we first show how the\nprogress of one step of the sketch-and-project method depends directly on a\nsketched residual. Based on this insight, we derive a 1) max-distance sampling\nrule, by sampling the sketch with the largest sketched residual 2) a\nproportional sampling rule, by sampling proportional to the sketched residual,\nand finally 3) a capped sampling rule. The capped sampling rule is a\ngeneralization of the recently introduced adaptive sampling rules for the\nKaczmarz method. We provide a global linear convergence theorem for each\nsampling rule and show that the max-distance rule enjoys the fastest\nconvergence. This finding is also verified in extensive numerical experiments\nthat lead us to conclude that the max-distance sampling rule is superior both\nexperimentally and theoretically to the capped sampling rule. We also provide\nnumerical insights into implementing the adaptive strategies so that the per\niteration cost is of the same order as using a fixed sampling strategy when the\nnumber of sketches times the sketch size is not significantly larger than the\nnumber of columns.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Sep 2019 02:59:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-10"}
