{"id":"1909.03687","submitter":"Oezge Drama","authors":"\\\"Ozge Drama and Alexander Badri-Spr\\\"owitz","title":"Trunk Pitch Oscillations for Joint Load Redistribution in Humans and\n  Humanoid Robots","comments":"IEEE Humanoids 2019 Submitted and Accepted, 6 pages, 9 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Creating natural-looking running gaits for humanoid robots is a complex task\ndue to the underactuated degree of freedom in the trunk, which makes the motion\nplanning and control difficult. The research on trunk movements in human\nlocomotion is insufficient, and no formalism is known to transfer human motion\npatterns onto robots. Related work mostly focuses on the lower extremities, and\nsimplifies the problem by stabilizing the trunk at a fixed angle. In contrast,\nhumans display significant trunk motions that follow the natural dynamics of\nthe gait. In this work, we use a spring-loaded inverted pendulum model with a\ntrunk (TSLIP) together with a virtual point (VP) target to create trunk\noscillations and investigate the impact of these movements. We analyze how the\nVP location and forward speed determine the direction and magnitude of the\ntrunk oscillations. We show that positioning the VP below the center of mass\n(CoM) can explain the forward trunk pitching observed in human running. The VP\nbelow the CoM leads to a synergistic work between the hip and leg, reducing the\nleg loading. However, it comes at the cost of increased peak hip torque. Our\nresults provide insights for leveraging the trunk motion to redistribute joint\nloads and potentially improve the energy efficiency in humanoid robots.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 9 Sep 2019 07:53:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-10"}
